"Since you're so fine with words," says the lieutenant to the diplomat in question, "perhaps you should explain our failure to Miss. Hannah Goode!"

children.value: The contract and those Pyrphorians must be here in Montoya, but where? The city sprawls before you under a pastel blue sky, the distinctive whitewall and terracotta of Imperial La Corona glowing softly all along the narrow estuary where the Mixcoatl meets the ocean. Yet, tranquil it is not. Anxiety is written in every passing face. They must know who you are and what you seek, but finding one brave enough to share is a different matter. You can ask around, or rely instead on your own eyes to find clues.

children.value: Your attaché hits it off with the harbourmaster, presenting you (not entirely falsely) as a fellow port official sympathetic to the Pyrphorian problem in the region. "I am sick of it," says the Montoyan, "whenever they come here it is a nightmare for us! If you take will action, it will be my pleasure to assist." Out on the sun-baked rooftop he points upriver. "There, at the casona." A large verdant ranch wavers in the distance, the sanctuary of the Pyrphorians.

Bullets ting through the many hundred stone representations of the goddess Pyr, as bodies drop on both sides. Eventually, the cultists prove too few. Having honoured the dead, you conduct a search. There is no contract, but a fiery oculus stares up from the floor, it is a Pyrphorian paper tract— an invitation to a rally at the Casado estate.

children.value: Your feeble bunch finally edge open the heavy door, only to find the building deserted. That it is owned by the Pyrphorians there is no doubt. Carmine drapes smother the windows, and your people find themselves picking over the cult's instruments, whose purpose is unsettlingly opaque. "What's this oily liquid on the floor," someone says, just as the door slams shut, and is followed by the hasty rattle of padlock and keys. The Pyrphorian fire will burn bright and long at the quayside this night. Only one of your crew return home.

You realise if that contract is anywhere, it is probably there.

children.value:
The Pyrphorian defence is short-lived, and your lose no-one. Leaving the dying Pyrphorians to bask in last light, you enter the house by the front door.
Your party meet with no resistance in the vestibule, only dread. It is a large open room, with stairs at either side. A series of Pre-Raphaelite panels depicting Pyr the fire mother adorn the walls. In one, she stands beneath a dark and cosmic sky, disciples at her feet, each holding a braid of her flaming hair. The most striking feature of the room however, is the dome in the centre, which from below appears at first convex, and is painted in every detail as a human eye. The Oculus. children.value:
"Correct." The guard sounds almost surprised. Your strides unopposed up the long tree-lined drive and right in through the main door.
Inside, your impostor meets with no resistance, only dread. It is a large open room, with stairs at either side. A series of Pre-Raphaelite panels depicting Pyr the fire mother adorn the walls. In one, she stands beneath a dark and cosmic sky, disciples at her feet, each holding a braid of her flaming hair. The most striking feature of the room however, is the dome in the centre, which from below appears at first convex, and is painted in every detail as a human eye. The Oculus. A pinprick of sunlight falls from its pupil to an ominous platform, thick with ash. You cannot find that contract soon enough.

children.value: Your brigade have the place to themselves. For a library there are very few books, and no sign of that contract under P for Prosperity, S for Sarmento, or anywhere else. The mahogany shelves are mostly home to objet d'art; cast iron animals never before seen, ornate weaponry, marble votives to Pyr. In the corner is the largest egg anyone has ever seen. It could be valuable, may as well have the men lift it before continuing your search.

children.value: Discouraged, the crew is forced to return to Isabel's island. "We lost them" apologises the captain. But a few days later, Isabel receives a letter from one of her scouting parties, 'Pyrphorian vessel spotted entering Montoya harbour." With renewed hope, the crew prepares to leave at once. The contract and those Pyrphorians must be here in Montoya, but where? The city sprawls before you under a pastel blue sky, the distinctive whitewall and terracotta of Imperial La Corona glowing softly all along the narrow estuary where the Mixcoatl meets the ocean. Yet, tranquil it is not. Anxiety is written in every passing face. They must know who you are and what you seek, but finding one brave enough to share is a different matter. You can ask around, or rely instead on your own eyes to find clues.

children.value: The sole survivor succeeds in getting back to Isabel's island. In his panic, he explains that the rest didn't make it, and describes how he traced the enemy back to an estate outside Montoya. A crew is assembled at once. They arrive to find the Casona looks quite modern, with its white walls and pleasant gables. The Prosperity contract must be here. An adjoining orangery extends naturally towards the neat parterres of a sweet-smelling garden. An arc of white gravel serves as a drive, and long lines of equally white picket border the acreage in typical colonial style. Indeed were it not for the unusual height of this perimeter, and the shelters abutting it at intervals— armed guards no doubt stationed in each— it would appear much as any other estate. You consider your plan of entry.

children.value: You know it's the wrong choice from the moment you walk into the parlour. The Duchess, who is of middle-age, lies half-asleep in a four-posted bed, which from her dishevilled appearance it seems she has not left in days. "Excuse my zurprise," she croaks, "But a Queen, come here? When our zide of the family has been neglected for years?" She feigns a tortured expression. "But now we have darling visitors!" Anxious not to offend, you remain in her company until she eventually tires of her games. She lets slip the Queen is visiting her cousin, Prince Ernest. The Prince offers you a cordial welcome at his ivy-clad castle, but appears twitchy throughout.

The Prince offers you a cordial welcome at his ivy-clad castle, but appears twitchy throughout.Exported132469

children.value: "From your movements, I sense that you too are worried for her welfare." The subtlety of your deduction surprises Prince Ernest. He nods silently, and falls heavily into the ornate chair behind his desk. "She asked me to help trace our shared lineage— to establish the validity of certain claims she has through her ancestral ties to La Corona." Ernest pauses and crunches nervously on some recently-acquired shortbread. "She had wanted to do it alone for once. But she risks herself, and I have now decided you must go after her— There is to be a masked ball in Monégasque. You will find her there.

children.value: Your strange deduction offends Prince Ernest. "From your movements, I sense this is a matter of the heart," is what you had said. Prince Ernest had then turned his back on you gothically, shouting — "How dare you; prying into her personal affairs, as they all did during the crushing confines of her youth!" — before storming into the gardens to sulk. The next day the Prince seems only very slightly calmer, "she asked me to help trace our family tree— that is all. I will not stop you going after her, in spite of your impertinence, only because I am concerned for her welfare. There is to be a masked ball in Monégasque. You will find her there."

children.value: The fruit-pickers don't believe you are who you threaten to be, and if anything, your surly attitude makes them wonder if it could be you the Queen is running away from. They call out to the rest of the pickers, who stand shoulder-to-shoulder with them in case you should think of taking things any further. Turning miserably back to your carriage in the road, it is only after considerable soul-searching that you re-read Sir Archibald's briefing, "despite her secrecy, a Queen never travels humbly." Of course, how stupid! One of the countless castles that dominate the hills all around. It is now but a question of exactly which of her landed relatives she came here to visit...

children.value: You have lost some face in royal circles. "I shall tell you nothing, nothing!" Prince Ernest says curtly, exhausted by your chatter, "yet another prying into her personal affairs, as so many did through the crushing confines of her youth!" The Queen's cousin then storms into the gardens to sulk. The next day he seems only very slightly calmer, "she asked me to help trace our family tree— that is all. I will not stop you going after her, in spite of your impertinence, only because I am concerned for her welfare. There is to be a masked ball in Monégasque. You will find her there."

children.value: Following Prince Ernest's advice, you travel by train along the sparkling Côte Turquoise to a grand station in the sophisticated principality of Monégasque. Ruled for six centuries by the Piedmont family, today the streets of Monégasque are filled with colour and light, for it is the grand opening of its very first casino! The theme is animal masquerade, and you see disturbing furred and feathered costumes at every turn. Convenient for a Queen going incognito... Prince Ernest gave you his own invitation to the casino, but you will also need a costume.

Trying to summon whatever remaining grace you have, you make your way inside the casino and debate your best bet for finding the Queen.

children.value: You comport yourself with dignity, "Your Majesty, please, I'm not here to seize you, but to assist you in any way I am able!" The short rotund figure turns, dresses in hand, and a small but shrill voice floats back towards you over the sound of the sea. "Meet me at the Cape of Trelawney!" You find your own ship at the marina, and sail to Trelawney, southernmost point of the Old World. It was not fifteen years previous, that a great naval victory was won here over La Corona by one Admiral Nadasky. The Lap of Victory is there waiting for you, and the Queen receives you warmly aboard. You are finally able to ask her why it is she has run away.

children.value: You cannot keep the irritation from your voice, "Your Majesty, please, desist from this charade!" The short rotund figure turns, dresses in hand, and a small but defiant voice floats cuts the sound of the sea. "I am not a child, I am your Queen! Be at the Cape of Trelawney tomorrow, or else." You slink off to find your ship at the marina and head for Trelawney, southernmost point of the Old World, where not fifteen years previous, a great naval victory was won over La Corona by the heroic Admiral Nadasky. The Lap of Victory is there waiting for you, and the Queen receives you rather icily aboard. With a gulp, you are finally able to ask why it is she has run away.

Slightly hurt, you point your ship towards Trelawney, southernmost point of the Old World, where not fifteen years previous, a great naval victory was won over La Corona by the heroic Admiral Nadasky. The Lap of Victory is there waiting for you, and the Queen receives you rather icily aboard. With a gulp, you are finally able to ask why it is she has run away.

children.value: The first severe blizzard. You have just caught sight of the Baffling Island littoral, when the headwind suddenly whips up and a dark fringe of cloud appears in the heavens. All take cover below deck, as rock-hard pellets of ice begin to pelt the ship with such force as to cause lasting damage. "We've lost control of her," screams the navigator, but it'd take a hero to go back out into that.

children.value: Worthy heroes step forward. "Whatever this ship and her crew needs," says the burliest, before striding out into the storm. Undeterred by the snow and buffeting of the wind, they put the sails 'in their gear'— loosing the sheetlines, and pulling the buntlines through, until the ship is running under jib alone. The storm passes, and the crew feel invincible.

children.value: Your men cannot keep their footing for the ice on deck, and the hard rocking of the ship gives them further excuse to lower their swords. They can only watch as, under the pull of the sails, the mainmast cracks open like grissini, the upper section cartwheeling out to sea, a tangle of rigging behind it. The crew are all accounted-for, but the damage to the ship is probably irreparable.

children.value: Filled with doubt, they do as instructed. The conditions are dreadful, and they can barely see to work in the sideways slather and what with the waves buffeting the ship. Finally, the sails are put up and the boat can ride out the remainder of the storm without blowing off course. Your crew are incensed at the coldness of their superiors.

children.value: Faith and prudence. Your sailors huddle below, rocked hard, but out of harm's way. They resist the temptation to attend the creaking ship and its rudder and trust their course to the divine. Soon the grog is flowing, sailors play at cribbage, and all forget where they be. "Hold! I hear no storm," a sailor says suddenly. The hatch is opened to reveal stillness and stars, and a harlequin snake of an aurora, smiling down benevolent.

children.value: Your sailors will not wait for god. The storm shrieks its name, as sailors muttered frenzied supplications to the nameless. "To hell and damn you all, I want to die living," the others bellow at them, and so unchained, they rush out into the white. Harsh commands can be heard above, before those voices fall silent. Somehow the ship rides out the storm, but the bodies of your saviours are never found.

The others named are "John Gore" and "Francis Seeley." Your men tremble at the idea of disturbing the graves.

children.value:
The crew agree to draw lots. A scrawny man gets the shovel, and clears snow to reveal Braine's face, who might look asleep but for his skin of leather. In his pocket, a letter to his wife.
Dearest Elaine,
I've few breaths left. I die never having found a Passage, but then no glory awaits any servant of Sir John. He was certain the ice would not thicken around us in Spring. Fate of expedition now rests on circumnavigation of Labrador Island by short, perilous west shore, or by long, open east channel— fear I know what Sir John will prefer.
Farewell my Elaine.

The crew agree to draw lots. A scrawny man gets the shovel, and clears snow to reveal Braine's face, who might look asleep but for his skin of leather. In his pocket, a letter to his wife.
Dearest Elaine,
I've few breaths left. I die never having found a Passage, but then no glory awaits any servant of Sir John. He was certain the ice would not thicken around us in Spring. Fate of expedition now rests on circumnavigation of Labrador Island by short, perilous west shore, or by long, open east channel— fear I know what Sir John will prefer.
Farewell my Elaine.Exported5

May 28th, 1847 { H.M. ships 'Styx' and 'Hades' wintered in the ice in lat. 70˚ 05' N ; long. 98˚ 23' W. Having wintered in 1846-7 at Baffling Island, in lat. 74˚ 43' 28" N., long. 91˚ 39' 15" W., after having sailed Wailing Channel to lat. 77˚, and returned by the west side of Cornell Island. Total loss by deaths to this date has been 3 men due to sickness — Braine, Gore and Seeley, God rest their souls. Leaving tomorrow for Labrador Island. Aim to reach Passage by end June; we must be close now. John Faithful, Commander, HMS Styx.

children.value: The inevitable splosh. Despite the cold wind, it is still summer in the Arctic, and the weight of a large group of bodies would test thicker ice than this. Halfway across the sheet, there is a rasping crack, and your men are deposited in the water. In their struggle to escape they have to kick off their snow boots. Chattering, they make it to the thin comfort of the abandoned trading post with their feet in a terrible state.

Dockets are found relating to consignments received from a nearby Inuit settlement named Ivujivik, which happens also to be marked on a fragment of map. "The Inuit are sure to have noticed anyone passing through," says the Captain, "we should visit them."

children.value:
It is late summer when the expedition reaches the Tchilling Sound, and yet the conditions in these icy seas are already challenging. The wind only has to pick up, and the men are tugging up their collars and tramping below. It seems hopeless to think Sir John Faithful's men could have lasted three winters here. Beyond Tchilling Sound, the seaway divides.
To the west lie a chain of small islands separated by partially melted ice.
To the south, a long, dark headland crowned with snow, that hazes out of sight.

children.value: Ivujivik is a semi-permanent settlement. The Inuit appear worried, but nevertheless offer your men every hospitality, inviting them into a large iglu where they are served a hearty Suaasat— a meat stew— under the silent gaze of what feels like the whole village. A girl, Tapeesa, is able to translate, and the others warm up when the hear the story of your journey over the ice flats. Soon the subject turns to Sir John's lost expedition. Tapeesa shows you items that look like they belonged to Sir John's expedition.

children.value: Your ship is stranded on an iceberg! It is night along the east coast of Labrador Island. The meek light of your vessel seems to dissolve into the moonless blackness. Even at easy sail and under constant vigil, your ship runs the risk here, for slumbering ice giants leer from the darkness in all directions. "Dead ahead!" comes the cry, too late! A low growl shakes the boat, as a wave dumps it atop a berg— in the shape of an upturned molar— beaching it there. The ship is undamaged, if only it could be returned to the water...

children.value: The crew assembles a dozen hardy levers to free the ship. Flexible hickory planking is cut and reshaped into a wedges, before being inserted into the ice at intervals of five paces, until they surround the stern. On a count of three the men lift, and to their surprise so does the hull! Once it starts moving, there's no stopping it; and it clatters through all icy obstructions to the sea. Your sailors embrace, they have been very resourceful.

children.value: The wrong wood is selected for the task. It is a decorative mahogany veneer, stripped from the captain's cabin. "Whatever it takes," the captain says with laudable magnanimity, but the whole business is futile. Despite the wedges being placed in great number at the stern of the ship, no amount of pressure from the crew can encourage the ship to move since the levers lack the requisite spring. They'll need to find another way off this berg.
